  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's inner-east suburbs are full of homes that have been extended, renovated, and reconfigured over the past few decades. A Queenslander in Morningside with a new deck, a rear extension on a postwar home in Carina, a carport built in the 1990s on a property in Camp Hill: many of these works were completed without the council approval they required at the time. When the property sells, those unapproved structures do not disappear from the title. They transfer to the buyer, along with the legal responsibility to address them.</p>

      <p>Understanding which of your renovations required council approval, whether that approval was obtained, and what your disclosure obligations are as a seller is not optional. It is part of preparing a property for sale properly, and it affects both your legal exposure and your ability to negotiate confidently.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What types of work require council approval in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>Under Brisbane City Council's planning and building regulations, a broad range of residential works require a building approval, a development approval, or both. Structural changes to the building are almost always in scope: removing load-bearing walls, adding a second storey, extending the footprint, enclosing a garage or carport to create habitable space, and adding a covered deck or pergola that is attached to the main structure. Swimming pools, spa pools, and their associated safety fencing require approval regardless of size.</p>

      <p>Carports and sheds above certain dimensions require approval, with the thresholds varying by lot size and position relative to the boundary. Significant electrical and plumbing work, including the addition of a new bathroom or the relocation of a kitchen with major drainage changes, generally requires a licensed tradesperson to certify the work and in many cases a building application as well. Retaining walls above 1 metre in height in the Brisbane City Council area typically require approval.</p>

      <p>The practical test is whether the work changes the structure, the use, or the drainage configuration of the property. Minor cosmetic work, such as repainting, recarpeting, replacing kitchen or bathroom fixtures on a like-for-like basis, and installing new flooring, generally does not require approval. Replacing windows and doors within the existing opening, without changing the opening size or the structural framing, is typically also exempt. If you are uncertain about specific work on your property, a private building certifier or your conveyancer can advise on the relevant requirements at the time the work was done.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to check whether your renovation was properly approved</h2>
      <p>The most reliable way to confirm whether building approval was obtained for work on your property is to search Brisbane City Council's online property search tool, which shows development applications and building approvals recorded against the address. You can also contact the council directly or engage a private building certifier to conduct a building records search.</p>

      <p>For older properties, records may be incomplete or may have been held by the private certifier who approved the work rather than by council. A certificate of classification, or a certificate of occupancy for older works, confirms that the relevant authority signed off on the completed structure. If you have paperwork from the builder, the certifier, or the original development application, that is the place to start. If the work was done by a previous owner and you have no records, a building certifier inspection and a council records search together will give you the clearest picture of what is and is not approved.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers must disclose about unapproved structures in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Queensland's property law requires sellers to complete a disclosure statement as part of the standard REIQ contract. This statement includes questions about whether the seller is aware of any material facts that could affect the buyer's decision to purchase. Unapproved structures on the property are generally considered a material fact that must be disclosed.</p>

      <p>Failing to disclose a known unapproved structure can expose a seller to a claim for misrepresentation or, in serious cases, the buyer seeking to rescind the contract after settlement. Your conveyancer will advise you specifically on your disclosure obligations based on the works on your property, but the general principle is straightforward: if you know about it, disclose it. Buyers who discover unapproved works after settlement and who can show the seller knew have legal options. Buyers who were told about the works before contracting generally do not.</p>

      <p>Disclosure does not necessarily derail a sale. Many buyers in Brisbane's inner-east market are experienced renovators who understand that older properties often carry unapproved works and who are comfortable taking on the responsibility of retrospective approval or regularisation. What matters is that they were informed before they committed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The cost and timeline of retrospective approval before listing</h2>
      <p>If you are aware of unapproved works on your property and you want to resolve them before listing, retrospective approval (sometimes called regularisation or show cause) is available for many types of residential work. The process involves engaging a private building certifier who inspects the structure, assesses whether it meets the relevant building code requirements at the time the work was done, and either certifies it or identifies what remediation is needed to bring it to standard.</p>

      <p>For straightforward structures that meet the code, retrospective approval can be completed in a few weeks and costs a few thousand dollars, depending on the scope of work. For more complex cases, or where the structure does not meet current standards, the certifier may require rectification work before certification can be issued. In some cases, particularly where a structure encroaches on a setback or exceeds a height limit by more than minor tolerances, retrospective approval may not be achievable, and you will need to weigh the cost of removal against the value of the structure to prospective buyers.</p>

      <p>Whether retrospective approval is worthwhile before your sale depends on the nature of the works, the likely buyer pool, and the price bracket. For a significant unapproved extension that adds meaningful living area to the property, sorting the paperwork before listing is usually the right call. For a small garden shed that is technically in scope but unlikely to concern any buyer, the time and cost of retrospective approval may not be justified. Your agent and your conveyancer can help you make that assessment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How buyers and their building inspectors identify unapproved works</h2>
      <p>Experienced building inspectors know what to look for. Inconsistencies in construction materials and methods, wall linings or insulation that do not match the age of the rest of the house, plumbing or electrical work that does not align with the main switchboard or the council records, and structures that are closer to boundaries than current regulations allow are all markers that prompt further investigation. In Brisbane's inner-east suburbs, where many homes have been bought, renovated, and on-sold multiple times, this kind of layered construction history is common.</p>

      <p>Buyers who discover unapproved works during their due diligence period will typically request a price reduction to account for the cost and risk of regularisation, or request that the seller obtain the relevant approvals before settlement. In a competitive market, they may proceed anyway on favourable terms. In a softer market, they may withdraw. The more transparent you are about the property's history from the outset of the campaign, the less likely those due diligence discoveries are to derail the negotiation.</p>

